{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580357/1949031001/0389.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\u2019\"\nlr\nThe bitter battle on the Senate\nfloor was openly predicted at the\nclose of the session of the Senate\nLabor Committee which approved\nthe Truman-Thomas bill. The vote\nwas along partisan lines, eight\nDemocrats voting against five Re\npublicans, and the Republicans\nloosed a blast of anguish after it\nwas over.\nAfter Sen. Elbert Thomas, the\ncommittee chairman, announced the\nvote and''said the bill was being\nmoved along as the American peo\nple had demanded, Sen. Robert\nTaft (R, Ohio) called it \u201cthe most\nhigh-handed procedure I have ever\nseen in Congress.\u201d\nHe said he had at least 19\namendments to the bill he wanted\nto offer and he knew that Sen.\nWayne Morse (R, Ore.) had as\nmany more he wanted to offer.\nThomas told newsmen it was ob\nvious the committee could go on\nuntil doomsday considering amend\nments if he let the Republicans\nhave their way.\n\u2019There have been repeated asser\ntions by observers here that the\nAdministration does not have the\nvotes to pass the Thomas Bill as it\nstands and repeal the T-H Act\nwithout some kind of compromise.\nThe committee vote, along party\nlines, meant that the Democratic\nmajority chose to rule out any com\npromise in committee and to fight\nit out on the Senate floor.\nThe House also began to move\nto'ward T-H repeal this week. The\nHouse Labor Committee\u2019s subcom\nmittee, headed by Rep. Augustine\nKelley (D, Pa.), was scheduled to\nbegin hearings this week on the\nAdministration\u2019s bill, with two con\ngressmen\u2014Pete Rodino (D, N.J.)\nwho is holding former Rep. Fred\nHartley\u2019s seat, and Rep. Steve\nYoung (D, Ohio).\nRep. Kelley said the hearings\nwill last ten days\u2014or two five-day\nweeks, with morning, afternoon,\nand evening sessions if necessary.\nBuy Union-Made goods fyom\nothers as you would have them\npay Union wages unto you!\nYou Can See the Cream\nALWAYS USE\nCREAM TOP\nMilk Baffles\nTHEY ARE SANITARY\nUsed Exclusively By\nGolden Star\nDairy\nPhone 3200\nvV\u2019*'\nu\nSenate Girds For Floor4\nBattle On Labor Bill\nHouse Begins Hearings\nWashington (LPA)\u2014Over still*-\u2014------------------------\ndetermined and persistent Republic\nopposition, the Truman-Thomas\nLabor Bill has moved out of the\nSenate Labor Committee and on to\nthe floor of the Senate.\nIn approving the Truman\nThomas bill just as it was origin\nally presented by Secretary of\nLabor Maurice Tobin weeks ago,\nthe Senate group opened the way\nfor the biggest hurdle facing the\nnew labor bill\u2014the fight in the\nSenate, which is expected to begin\nwitMn the next few weeks and will\ncertainly be a long and extremely\nbitter battle.\nAfter that the Truman plan for\nlabor relations should face relative\nly smooth sailing, since the Admin\nistration believes it has the votes\nto pass the bill in the House, which\nis much more agreeable to the Ad\nministration\u2019s program than the\nSenate.\n'Unera\nCots\nNewspaper Guild\nAnnounces Annua\nAward Winners\nIZllllfl\nNew York (LPA)\u2014The Ameri\ncan Newspaper Guild has ann\nounced the winners of its annual\nawards for \u201coutstanding journal\nistic achievement in the spirit of\nHeywood Broun.\u201d\nWinner of the first prize of $500\nwas Elias A. McQuaid, of the Man\nchester, N. H. News, a weekly, who\ntook a routine assignment and fol\nlowed it up to expose how $700,000\nin state contracts had been let\nwithout bids. As a result of his\nsearching stories, which rocked\nNew Hampshire, two state officials\nhave been indicted and the state is\nsuing to recover $250,000 from the\nformer state comptroller for al\nleged overpayments to\ning firm.\nOther special awards went to\nAlan Barth, editorial writer for\nthe Washington Post, for his ser\nies of editorials on the civil libert\nies problems raised by government\nattempts to deal with the threats\nto national security, and to Walt\nKelly, cartoonist of the now dead\nNew York Star, for a series of\ncartoons during the presidential\ncampaign pointing up the issues\ninvolved.\nGibson Resigns\nFroHi Labor Post\nWashington (LPA) Assistant\nSecretary of Labor John W. Gib\nson, has confirmed rumors here\nthat he is resigning his post.\nGibson, who at 38 has been an\nenergetic worker in the Truman\nAdministration labor circles, said\nlast week that he had forwarded\nhis resgination to the White House\nin January, but had no word on its\nacceptance.\nGibson has been prominently\nmentioned as a candidate for the\npost of Under-Secretary of Labor,\nwhich has been vacant since David\nMorse became head of the Int\u2019l\nLabor Organization of the United\nNations.\nGibson's appointment to the Job\nis reported to have been opposed\nby the A FL, and last week the\nquestion wiu settled by the lam\nination of Michael J. Galvin, a Bos\nton attorney, to the post. Galvin\nappeared before the Senate Labor\nCommittee last week and his name\nwas approved and sent to the Sen\nate floor for final confirmation,\nwhich was expected shortly.\nGibson is said to be considering\nseveral future positions, both in\n|and out of government.\nACTUAL charges for 500 consecu\ntive funerals conducted by the\nDAWSON\nfollowsl\nFuneral Home are as\nWere\n9% Were\n50% Were\n31% Were\nDawson\n\u201cSO MUCH lot ao little*\n215 West Fifth Street Phone Main 10\nlource:\nUnder $150\nUnder $300\nUnder $500\nOver $500\nFuneral Home\ntV?' ,r\n7^\nMMtW\nCmc\na contract-\ncommittee,\nColumnist\nThe Guild awards\nwhich included LPA\nNathan Robertson, also made addi\ntional awards for three newspaper\nworkers. They were Theodore C.\nLink of the St. Louis Post-Dis\npatch, for his expose of graft and\ncorruption in Illinois, which helped\ndefeat Gov. Green and his attorney\ngeneral last November Don Mag\nnuson, of the Seattle Times, for\nfollowing up an ordinary letter to\nthe editor and freeing a man from\na prison term for a murder he did\nnot commit Drew Pearson, of the\nWashington Merry-Go-Round, for\nhis series of columns which result\ned in an indictment of Rep. J. Par\nnell Thomas (R, NJ) on charges\nof payroll padding.\nEconomic\nHappenings That Affect the Dinner\nPails, Dividend Checks and Tax\nBills of Every Individual National\nand International Problems Insep\narable From Local Welfare\nThe attention of many members\nof Congress seems to be wavering\nfrom Mr. Truman\u2019s langrange leg\nislative program, and turning to\nthe immediate problem of just what\ncurrent declines in prices, employ\nment and business activity mean.\nSome of the drop can be attri\nbuted to seasonal factors. But that\ndoesn\u2019t account for all of it by\nquite a ways. Congress wants to\nget a clearer idea of what is going\non before it does much law making.\nThe House-S e n a e Economic\nCommittee recently called in a\nnumber of leading economists and\nasked for their opinions and advice.\nAs was to be expected, there were\nmany differences. But the majority\nof these experts were agreed that\nwe have passed the peak of infla\ntion, and that a levelling off period\nis now at hand. However, there\nwas little talk to the effect that a\nsevere recession is imminent.\nOne of them, representing a\nlarge life insurance company, anti\ncipated a long period of good\ntimes, though he added that the\nbuyers\u2019 market is back and the\nconsumer will have to be induced\nto buy. Another, from a publishing\nhouse which issues magazines\ndealing with industrial questions,\nsaid he doesn\u2019t fear that a serious\ndownturn is coming, and warned\nagainst raising taxes. The econ\nomist for a steel company argued\nthat a big backlog of demand, left\nover from the war days, is still in\nevidence, and was optimistic as to\nthe future. A pessimistic note was\nstruck by the economist from a na\ntional research organization, who\nwas none too sure that we have an\neasy road ahead.\nThe point on which most agreed\nwas that there should be no tax\nincreases, either on business or on\nindividuals. The reason: these bur\ndens, they think, might prove to be\nsufficient to turn a moderate and\ntemporary decline in business\nactivity into a real recession. The\nPresident has said that nothing\nthat has happen'd has changed his\nview on the tax problem, and Con\ngress should approve his proposal\nfor raising $4,000,000,000 through\nnew taxes. But there are many\ngrave doubts among members of\nboth parties.\nSentiment is increasing for mak\ning up possible budget deficits by\nreducing the cost of government.\nThe Hoover Commission reports,\nwhich have been issued so far,\nhave shown up serious waste which\ncould be eliminated without touch\ning any essential function. Dupli\ncation of bureaus, archaic proce\ndures, the abuse of patronage\u2014\nthese are old vices which the Com\nmission hopes may be cured. Mr.\nHoover\u2019s idea is that the President\nshould have far greater direct\npowers over the machinery of the\ngovernment. It is not likely that\nall of the recommendations will be\napproved. But a start will be made.\nPittsburgh Typos\nWin $5 Pay Boost\nPittsburgh (LPA)\u2014Members of\nLocal 7, of the International Typo\ngraphical Union employed on three\ndaily newspapers here have won $5\nweekly raises and increased vaca\ntion benefits in negotiations ending\nwith a ratification vote by the local\nmembers last week.\nThe ITU members, employed at\nthe Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph, the\nPost Gazette, and the Pittsburgh\nPress, voted 207 to 32 to accept\nthe pay increase and the three\nweeks vacation clause for men with\nmore than five years service. The\ncontract, which is for one year re\ntroactive to January 1, will give\nthe men $95 for day work on a\n37 hour week, and $99 for night\njobs.\nBuy Union-Made goods from\nothers as you would have them\npay Union wages unto youl\nlMf\\\nWIN\nof food basket calculated by Labor Department Consumer Price Index.\nHighlights\nDoctors Insist\nProgram Short\nOf Health Needs\nBaltimore (LPA)\u2014The Ameri\ncan Medical Association\u2019s 12-point\nprogram is not an adequate sub\nstitute for the health insurance\nproposals put forward by the Tru\nman Administration, a group of\n136 prominent physicians asserted\nlast week.\nThe physicians, including many\nof the nation\u2019s top doctors at Johns\nHopkins University Hospital here,\nhad earlier protested the AMA\u2019s\n$25-a-member assessment to fight\nthe national health insurance pro\ngram.\n\u201cUntil the association\u2019s propos\nals encompass a plan for the entire\ncountry which can provide com\nprehensive preventive and curative\nservices for persons of moderate\nincome as well as to the indigent,\nwe believe that the public will not\nregard the program of the AMA\nas an adequate alternative for com\npulsory medical insurance,\u201d they\nstated. They want a conference of\ndoctors, consumers, labor and\nother groups to work out an alter\nnative plan. At another point in\ntheir statement, in which they\nmade it clear they opposed the\nAdministration plan, the doctors\nsaid the AMA\u2019s 12 points \u201cfall far\nshort\u201d of meeting the nation\u2019s\nmedical care needs.\nThe same criticism applies to a\nproposal advanced by Dr. Paul\nMagnuson of Veterans Administra\ntion, according to a spokesman for\nCommittee for the Nation\u2019s Health.\nMagnuson called his a \u201cmiddle\nway\u201d between the AMA\u2019s plan and\nthe health insurance plan. Primar\nily, it would set up free diagnostic\nclinics and hospitals all over the\ncountry, and would have the feder\nal and state governments make up\nany deficit between what individ\nuals can pay their doctors, and the\ncost of treatment recommended\nthe free clinics.\nby\nDrive Underway\nFor Fourth Round\nWage Increase\nWashington (LPA)\u2014The Com\nmunications Workers of America,\nrepresenting 230,000 workers\nacross the country, got off its four\nth-round wage increase drive this\nweek when the union\u2019s New Jersey\nTraffic Division served its request\nfor an increase on the N. J. Bell\nTelephone Co. for immediate nego\ntiation.\nInternational President Joseph\nA. Bierne said tb^t as other con\ntracts come up for renewal the\nunion will ask pay boosts along\nwith other contract modifications.\nCWA leaders said telephone\nworkers are behind other workers\nin straight pay, altho some of them\nare ahead in other benefits like\npensions, sick leave, holiday pay,\nand vacations.\nCWA\u2019s wage increase campaign\nwill go on thru the summer and\npick up momentum in the fall, when\na considerable number of its affili\nates will be able to reopen their\ncontracts.\nTruman Still For Inflation Checks\nWashington (LPA) It\u2019s still\nnecessary to have the controls that\nwere asked of Congress in early\nJanuary, President Truman told\nhis press conference last week.\nAnd at the other end of the capitol\npreparations were being made to\nopen hearings on his stabilization\nmeasure on March 16 before the\nSenate Banking Committee. His\nproposals include authority to call\nfor a 90-day \u201ccooling off period\u201d on\nprice changes on vital and scarce\ngoods, and power to control prior\nities and allocations of these scarce\ngoods.\nDemand the Uniog Label*\n.J&L\ntv:-\nTHE POTTERS HERALD, EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\n-ALT\nMTHM\n_.....\n3\nMffH *74*\nHouse Voting On\nRent Control Bill\nThat\u2019s Too Weak\nWashington (LPA) Only 27\ndays before the present law ex\npires, a badly battered rent control\nbill was reported out of the House\nBanking Committee for floor\naction, while o.n the Senate side the\nBanking subcommittee headed by\nSen. Sparkman (D, Ala.) started\nweek-long hearings on rent control\nmeasures.\nMajor damage done to the rent\ncontrol program in the House com\nmittee was when all criminal pen\nalties were removed from the bill.\n\u201cThis is like an advance notice to\nany landlord that he\u2019ll only get his\nwrist slapped if he goes out and\nwilfully violates the law,\u201d com\nmented one union spokesman.\nThe measure would be in effect\nfor only 15 months, instead of the\ntwo years asked by the Adminis\ntration.\nHowever, the rent control admin\nistrator would be given the right\nto sue for treble damages in the\ncase of wilful overcharges, a right\nnow given only to the actual ten\nant. And a proposal to control per\nmanent trailer housing rents was\nadded to the measure in commit\ntee.\nAn additional threat is the grow\ning movement to write into the bill\na guarantee of a \u201cfair return\u201d to\n\u2022vsfry landlord on every rental pro\nperty he owns. While this was beat\nen back by a close vote in the\nHouse committee, it is expected to\nbe raised again on the floor, and\nin the Senate committee.\nThe Senate subcommittee will\nhear this week from AFL and CIO,\nas well as from other public inter-\u2019\nest groups who support a strong\nbill. Landlords will also be out ini\nforce, though most of their atten\ntion1 seems centered on behind-the-\u2019\nscenes pressure rather than a pub\nlic fight. They are relying on\nchanges in technicalities\u2014which\nmay look unimportant but actually\nare essential parts of rent control*\n\u2014to save their profits.\nThe profits position of the land\nlords got a good deal of attention\nfrom Housing Expediter Tighe\nWoods when he led off before the\nSenate subcommittee. Woods said\nthat under rent controls no land\nlord should lose money, since \u201cour\nadjustment provisions permit any\nlandlord to secure the net operating\nincome that he enjoyed during his\nbest two-year period since 1939.\nWhere landlords\u2019 operating posi\ntion has declined generally in an\narea as compared with the max\nimum rent date, local advisory\nboards may recommend general\nrent increases to compensate for\nthis decline.\nWoods\u2019 proposals for the Admin\nistration are for a two year exten\nsion, and for authority to the ad\nministrator to bring treble damage\nsuits for wilful overcharges, apply\ncriminal sanctions for wilful viola\ntions, and regulate 'evicttons. He\nwants permanent dwelling units in\nhotels and housing units not rented\nfor a 24 month period brought\nback under control and control\nkept on converted units except\nin specific cases where conver\nsion results in additional self\ncontained family units. He wants\npower to recontrol areas and esta\nblish controls in new areas where\nthis is warranted by the national\ndefense program or other chang\ning conditions. The provision for\nvoluntary leases should be dropped.\nAlso before the committee is the\nMyers-Douglas bill, which is much\nstronger and far-reaching. This is\nexpected to have the backing of\nthe unions which will appear this\nweek.\nJOB BARRIERS LOWERING\nChattanooga (LPA)\u2014Employers\nwith large sums of money tied up\nin plants are beginning to think\nleas about the color of machine op\nerators according to findings of\nthe Nat\u2019l Urban League. Several\nstates have lowered racial restric\ntions in job placement during the\npast months as a result of \u201cshort\nage of white personnel and the pre\nsence of army trained negro mech\nanics/\u2019\n.srh-v* *'4\nOBITUARIES\nMRS. MARY J. WALLACE\nMrs. Mary Jane Wallace, 79,\ndied March 6 in the home of her\ndaughter, Mrs. Earl Tweed, 115\nWest Third Street, following a long\nillness.\nMrs. Wallace was born at Free\nmans Ferry and came to East Liv\nerpool when a child. She was em\nployed as a ware dresser at Taylor,\nSmith Taylor pottery until she\nretired about six years ago.\nShe was a member of Local\nUnion 94, National Brotherhood of\nOperative Potters, First Church of\nChrist, and Council 7, Daughters of\nAmerica. s\nMrs. Wallace leaves two other\ndaughters, Mrs. Lola Kirkham of\nLos Angeles, and Edith Traub of\nEast Liverpool two sons, Otis\nWallace and William Wallace of\nEast Liverpool a brother, James\nMartin of Fairmont, W. Va., and\neight grandchildren and three\ngreat-grandchildren.\nServices were held from the\nAmer Home for Funerals, Rev. D.\nPark Chapman, officiating. Burial\nwas in Riverview Cemetery.\nHOMER C. MOORE\nHomer C. Moore, 667 Lincoln\nAve., an employee of the Sterling\nChina Co. died March 5 in City\nHospital, following a month\u2019s ill\nness. He was 45.\nMr. Moore was a member of\nLocal Union 24, National Brother\nhood of Operative Potters.\nHe leaves his widow, Mrs. Mil\ndred Cain Moore three sons, Har\nold Moore, Donald Moore and Rich\nard Moore, and two daughters,\nMrs. Richard Bourne and Helen\nMoore his mother, Mrs. Bate B.\nMoore, and a brother, Clyde Moore,\nall of East Liverpool, and\ngrandchildren.\ntwo\nthe\nServices were held from\nMartin Funeral Home. Burial\nin Riverview Cemetery.\nwas\nRALPH H. ELLIOTT\nHopewell, Va.\u2014Ralph H. Elliott,\n66, of 2900 Fendall Ave., a retired\npotter died at his home following\na short illness.\nMr. Elliott before moving to\nHopewell was employed at the\nCanonsburg Pottery.\nHe is survived by his wife, Mrs.\nLillian Dillon Elliott three daugh\nters, Mrs. Dorothy Ruis and Miss\nBernice Elliott, of Richmond, and\nMrs. Thelma Dyer, of Petersburg\nthree sons, C. C. Elliott of Hope\nwell J. S. Elliott of Hampton, and\nR. A. Elliott of Miami Beach, Fla.\na sister, Mrs. Frank Parsons of\nPittsburgh, Pa., and six grand\nchildren. 1\nEMERSON S. BOWMAN\nEmerson S. Bowman, 1514 St.\nClair Ave., died March 7 in City\nHospital following a lingering ill\nness. He was 80 years of age.\nMr. Bowman was born in East\nLiverpool, a son of the late David\nThomas and\nBowman.\nJamima Frances Orr~\ncaster by trade and\nHe wag a\nemployed in the pottery industry\nfor 63 years, 23 of which he was\nemployed at the Hall China Co. be\nfore his retirement in 1941.\nMr. Bowman will be remembered\nby his many friends as the winner\nof the oldest potter award at the\n1947 annual outing of the Broth\nerhood.\nHe was a member of Local Union\nNo. 4, National Brotherhood of\nOperative Potters, First Methodist\nChurch and Sunday School, and\nAsbury Power Closs.\nSurviving are two daughters,\nMrs. Zora Bowman Lewis of East\nLiverpool, and Mrs. La Rue Bow\nman Mooney at the late home a\nsister, Mrs. Elizabeth Cochrane\nGould of East Palestine, and two\ngrandchildren and one great-grand\nchild.\nPay Boost Ends\nVirginia\u2019s Seizure\nQf Transit Lines i\nRichmond, Va. (ILNS).\u2014Seized\nproperties of the Virginia Transit\nCo. in Richmond, Norfolk and\nPortsmouth were returned to the\nVirginia Transit Co. March 2 after\na month\u2019s operation under a seizure\norder by the state. Transit facil\nities were seized Feb. 3 by order\nof Gov. Tuck when nearly 1,600 op\nerators declared a strike. All of the\nmen consented to remain at their\nposts as employes of the Common\nwealth, and service has continued.\nThe operators, members of the\nAmalgamated Association of\nStreet, Electric Railway and Motor\nCoach Employes of America, voted\nto accept a new wage offer from\nthe company, providing for a wage\nincrease of 4 cents an hour, retro\nactive to Jan. 1, plus an additional\n3% cents May 31, if fare increases\nare obtained. The top rate is now\n1.14 to an hour.\nDuring the period of state seiz\nure, the company paid to the Com\nmonwealth 15 percent of its net\nrevenues as a service fee. The pro\ncedure was conducted under Vir\nginia\u2019s 1947 Public Utility Labor.\nRelations Act, which organized]\nlabor has vigorously opposed,\nWashington (LPA)\u2014Proof that*\ncollective bargaining, unhampered\nby injunctions, can solve a labor\ndispute threatening the national\nwelfare, was sent this week to the\nSenate Labor Committee consider\ning repeal of Taft-Hartley.\nIn a telegram to committee chair\nman Elbert Thomas (D, Utah),\nHerman E. Cooper, general counsel\nof Utility Workers called his at\ntention to a peaceful settlement,\nthe day before, of the dispute be\ntween the union and Consolidated\nEdison Co. of New York City.\nA strike vote had been taken at\nConsolidated Edison but, just one\nday before the deadline, agreement\nwas reached leaving nothing to\narbitration except permanent griev\nance machinery, and leaving the\npresent pension system intact while\nthe details for a permanent one are\nsettled by a committee. The 28_,000\nemployes of CE won a wage in\ncrease* of 7c to 12c.\nJThe strike, Cooper pointed out,\n\u201cwould have paralyzed the life of\nmetropolitan New York, with dam\naging impact upon the whole na\ntion.\n\u201cConfronted by their mutual res\nponsibility to the public,\u201d he said,\n\u201cthe union and management con\ntinued in negotiation with the aid\nof representatives of Mayor\nO\u2019Dwyer of New York and the\nFederal Mediation Conciliation\nService, which culminated in agree\nment on all issues.\n\u201cThe President was not required\nto apply the provisions of the Taft\nHartley law applicable to national\nemergencies of this character. No\ninjunction was either sought or re\nquired. Had the parties- been com\npelled to negotiate in the atmos\nphere of such government interven\ntion, the injunctive period might\nwell have served, as in other situa\ntions, to have stalled agreement\nand to provide discord, rather than\nthe harmony which here led to\nagreement.\u201d\nDemand the Union Label.\nTEAM UP\nriMt\nOF EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\nCERAMI\nnd*ek\u2019nea\"\nA LZOHAfW\n-A V\nThursday, March 10, 1949\nPOWER STRIKE AVERTED\nWITHOUT INJUNCTIONS\nA 111A\nI I allvlllvvll MU tv\nDealers Under\nT-H Board Rules\nWashington (LPA)\u2014The Nat\u2019l\nLabor Relations Board has ruled\nthat franchised dealers in new\nautomobiles come under the pro\nvisions of the Taft-Hartley act in\ninterstate commerce.\nOver-ruling the recommendation\nof a trial examiner, the board un-i\nanimously decided that a Cali-*\nfornia automobile dealer, M. LJ\nTownsend, of Santa Maria, wan\nwithin the law in his quarrel with\nthe Int\u2019l Association of Machinists.\nThe board ordered the examiner\nto prepare a recommended order\non the merits of charges by the\nI AM that the company has been\nguilty of unfair labor practices.\nThe IAM has charged Townsend'\nwith firing three employes for\nunion activity, questioning em\nployes about union .affiliation, spy\ning on meetings of employes, urg\ning employes to quit the union,\nand threatening discharge of those\nwho joined the union.\nBuy Union-Made goods from\nothers .as you would have them\npay Union wages unto you!\nDOCTOR SHOES\nFOR FOOT\nCOMFORT\nFlexible and\nrigid arch\nstyles tn ox\nfords and\nhigh s o e a\nX-ray Fitting\nBENDHEIM'S\nEast Sixth Street\nAND LOAN ASSOCIATION\nDays Commencing Thursday\n1032 Pennsylvania Ava(*aa\nproduetton\nSaw. Vbf ty MAR6U\u00a3Air\u00a3 flOMRTS on itory by FREDERICK. NE66L\nW'C(MnvROratrZ.l\u00a3OAMJU fWucedhr BBBMAM\nA Acturo-\njTMMMBNNnninIMmMliHiHiHiiaHiilNiiiuiiiiiiiiii wlniiillUillilnmllWlNwNHMmNHnNnHMMMMnHlllllNMIM^MMtMMNRNN^ii\nPOLKA DOT PUSS\u2014Colored Cartoon\nCHICAGO THE BEAUTIFUL\nSelected Short Feature\nNews of the Day In Pictures\nContinuous Show Saturday and Sunday\n.vTMT,\n\u25a0B","height":"26259","width":"21024"}}
